We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
a.	Require the Disbursing Officer to liquidate immediately her outstanding cash advances and practice the prompt liquidation of the same;

b.	Instruct the Municipal Accountant to closely monitor the outstanding cash advances and issue demand letters for its immediate liquidation or settlement;

c.	Refrain from granting additional cash advances if the Accountable Officer has unliquidated cash advances; 

d.	Coordinate with the barangays/intended payees/recipients on the schedule of pay-out to achieve the maximum number of distributions; and

e.	Ensure the proper granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances in accordance with the rules and regulations as provided in COA Circular No. 97-002 to avoid sanctions provided by law.

We have recommended that the Management thru the Local Chief Executive:

a.	Direct the Municipal Accountant to issue Demand Letters to beneficiaries of the Livelihood Program for the payment of their loans as reported under the Accounts Receivable;

b.	 Enforce payment or cause the deduction from the salaries of employees still connected with the Municipality for the settlement of their excess claims for travelling expenses;

c.	Exhaust all possible remedies available to collect from the persons liable who are separated or deceased, such as resorting to all legal remedies available to the LGU; and

d.	Strictly comply with Section 6.1 of COA Circular 2016-005 and pertinent provisions of COA Circular 2012-004 on the regular monitoring and analysis of receivable accounts to ensure that these are collected when due and the immediate liquidation and settlement of all cash advances.

We have recommended that the Management:

a.	Thru the Inventory Committee, conduct physical inventory of all items of PPE of the Municipality, whether acquired through purchase or donation, including those constructed by administration and found at station, within the period prescribed under the aforementioned COA Circular;

b.	Update the property records based on the results of physical inventory, and reconcile the same with accounting records to make the records reflective of the actual count of PPEs;

c.	Undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and 

d.	Direct the GSO Designate to prepare, maintain and update Property Cards for each item of the PPE pursuant to Section 114, Paragraph 4 of the MNGAs for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended the Local Chief Executive, being charged with official responsibility of ensuring that all resources of the LGU shall be managed, expended or utilized in accordance with law and regulations, and safeguarded against loss or wastage through illegal or improper disposition, the following:

•	Require the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to identify all persons liable for the undeposited balance of Cash in Local Treasury (old) account amounting to P2,954,782.77 and subsequently issue demand letters to the concerned accountable officers for the immediate remittance/deposit of the same;
•	Instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the same to the appropriate Receivable account once the accountabilities of the persons liable are definitely established by the OIC-Municipal Treasurer;

•	Exhaust all possible legal remedies to collect from the concerned accountable officers the total amount reported under Cash in Local Treasury-Old account and the same should be deposited the with the authorized government depository bank of the Municipality to avoid loss and misappropriation of government funds.

