We recommended management thru the Local Chief Executive the following:

1.	Strengthen its internal rules and regulations over its cash management to ensure that funds of the government are adequately safeguarded from possible misuse, misappropriation, irregularities and theft;

2.	Issue written rules and regulations which include the imposition of sanctions and penalties pertinent to the operations of the Treasury Office that are consistent with existing laws, rules and regulations, especially in the issuance of accountable forms to AOs, collection and deposit procedures requiring intact and daily/regular remittance/deposit of collections; 

3.	Require the OIC - Municipal Treasurer to monitor strictly the collections of the AOs by verifying the Report of Collections and Deposits as to initial balances on hand, receipts, sales and issues, and the new balances on hand; make a physical count of the accountable forms remaining in the custody of the Collector/Teller; and check the same to the new balances on hand column and issue Accountable Forms only to those Accountable Officers (AOs) who have completely remitted their collections;

4. 	Instruct the OIC - Municipal Treasurer to exercise the diligence of a good father of a family in supervising accountable officers under her control as well as diligently monitoring accountable forms and reports to avoid becoming jointly and severally liable together with erring collectors and designated collectors in case of loss of government funds;

We recommended management to implement the following: 
a.	The Inventory Committee should conduct annual physical inventory to include all the PPEs of the LGU and prepare properly and completely the corresponding RPCPPE;
b.	The General Services Office should maintain Property Cards, respectively, for all PPE Accounts;
c.	The Municipal Accountant should prepare and maintain the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards for each category of assets and Real Property Ledger Cards for land to back up the general ledger for PPE;
d.	The Accounting and General Services Offices should reconcile their records to obtain the accurate value of the PPE, prepare the required supporting documents, and draw the adjusting journal entries for the inventory items remaining in the books of accounts but are already non-existent due to fair wear and tear, thereby fairly present the balance of the property accounts in the financial statements.

