Instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the same to the appropriate Receivable account once the accountabilities of the persons liable are definitely established by the OIC-Municipal Treasurer;
Exhaust all possible legal remedies to collect from the concerned accountable officers the total amount reported under Cash in Local Treasury-Old account and the same should be deposited the with the authorized government depository bank of the Municipality to avoid loss and misappropriation of government funds.

We recommended management thru the Local Chief Executive the following:
Strengthen its internal rules and regulations over its cash management to ensure that funds of the government are adequately safeguarded from possible misuse, misappropriation, irregularities and theft;
Issue written rules and regulations which include the imposition of sanctions and penalties pertinent to the operations of the Treasury Office that are consistent with existing laws, rules and regulations, especially in the issuance of accountable forms to AOs, collection and deposit procedures requiring intact and daily/regular remittance/deposit of collections;
Require the OIC - Municipal Treasurer to monitor strictly the collections of the AOs by verifying the Report of Collections and Deposits as to initial balances on hand, receipts, sales and issues, and the new balances on hand; make a physical count of the accountable forms remaining in the custody of the Collector/Teller; and check the same to the new balances on hand column and issue Accountable Forms only to those Accountable Officers (AOs) who have completely remitted their collections;
Instruct the OIC - Municipal Treasurer to exercise the diligence of a good father of a family in supervising accountable officers under her control as well as diligently monitoring accountable forms and reports to avoid becoming jointly and severally liable together with erring collectors and designated collectors in case of loss of government funds;

We recommended management to implement the following:
The Inventory Committee should conduct annual physical inventory to include all the PPEs of the LGU and prepare properly and completely the corresponding RPCPPE;
The General Services Office should maintain Property Cards, respectively, for all PPE Accounts;
The Municipal Accountant should prepare and maintain the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards for each category of assets and Real Property Ledger Cards for land to back up the general ledger for PPE;
The Accounting and General Services Offices should reconcile their records to obtain the accurate value of the PPE, prepare the required supporting documents, and draw the adjusting journal entries for the inventory items remaining in the books of accounts but are already non-existent due to fair wear and tear, thereby fairly present the balance of the property accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that management strictly comply with the provisions embodied in the COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 25, 2015 and IPSAS 17 by ensuring the following:
a.	Inventory Committee conducts inventory of Local Roads under the LGUs jurisdiction at year-end;
b.	General Service Officer maintains and updates a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all road and its component;
c.	Municipal Engineer provides the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components of road projects; and
d.	Municipal Accountant ensures compliance with the transitory provisions of the Circular by updating the records of the Road Network account and keeps and maintains subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network. Moreover, the Municipal Accountant must compute the depreciation expense, prepare the lapsing schedule and draw necessary journal entry to take up depreciation expense for the current year, update the related accumulated depreciation and record adjustment in government equity account for unrecorded prior years’ depreciation expense to present fairly the financial statements in accordance with IPSAS 17.

